{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6c0e05dc-5497-470f-ab87-e559e2ab4717","content":"Yes, both are known MSTest v4 breaking changes. Here's what's happening:\n\n---\n\n## 1. Tests lost history in Azure DevOps\n\nMSTest v4 changed the **test-ID algorithm**. Every test gets a new ID, so ADO treats them as brand-new. To restore history, opt back in to the legacy IDs in your `.runsettings`:\n\n```xml\n<MSTest>\n  <TestIdGenerationStrategy>Legacy</TestIdGenerationStrategy>\n</MSTest>\n```\n\nOr accept the one-time break and keep the new stable IDs going forward.\n\n---\n\n## 2. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`\n\nIn v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` / `[AssemblyInitialize]` is **no longer test-specific** — there's no single test running yet. Accessing `TestName`, `TestResultsDirectory`, etc. now throws `InvalidOperationException`.\n\n**Fix for your code** — remove the dependency on `TestName` in `ClassInit`:\n\n```csharp\n[ClassInitialize]\npublic static void ClassInit(TestContext context)\n{\n    // context.TestName is not available here in v4\n    // Use context for class-level logging only\n}\n```\n\nIf you need per-test setup, use `[TestInitialize]` instead.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Other v4 changes to watch for\n\n| Area | Change |\n|------|--------|\n| **Parallelism** | Default is now `ExecutionScope.Class` (tests in different classes run in parallel). Set `[Parallelize(Scope = ExecutionScope.Method)]` or disable if you have shared state. |\n| **Timeout** | `[Timeout]` now applies to the test method only, not setup/cleanup. Infinite-timeout constant was removed. |\n| **Assert.AreEqual on collections** | More strict equality; use `CollectionAssert` for order-insensitive comparisons. |\n| **DataRow display names** | Display-name format changed, which can also affect test-result matching in CI. |\n| **TestContext.Properties** | No longer writable in some contexts. |\n\n---\n\nWould you like me to update your `SetupTests.cs` to be v4-compatible?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5763609c-58a2-4020-b5ff-53ed912bed56","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I can see the issue clearly. Let me explain the known MSTest v4 breaking changes that are relevant here.\n\n1. **Test ID changes (tests appearing as new)**: In MSTest v4, the default test ID generation algorithm changed to produce \"stable\" IDs. However, this means old test IDs no longer match the new ones, so Azure DevOps sees them as entirely new tests with no history. You can opt back into the legacy ID scheme.\n\n2. **TestContext.TestName in [ClassInitialize]**: In MSTest v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` and `[AssemblyInitialize]` methods is no longer associated with a specific test. Accessing `TestContext.TestName` (or other test-specific properties) in those methods now throws an `InvalidOperationException` because there's no individual test running at that point — it's a class-level setup.\n\n\n3. Beyond these two, there are several other breaking changes worth being aware of when upgrading to v4.","outputTokens":780,"requestId":"9C43:18BE1:1948E4D:1C39A9C:69F86C18"},"id":"297f5d16-29a6-4a05-a220-34001946dbb6","timestamp":"2026-05-04T09:51:40.910Z","parentId":"0813eb39-f130-4199-9045-fa3b2d8864b2"}
